raw_data.title: Sr. Engineer Consultant
raw_data.description: The Sr. Engineering Consultant must have extensive engineering experience in either biometrics; forensics; force protection; military command, control and communications; requirements analysis; advanced war fighting concepts, doctrine, tactics, techniques, and procedures; or computer systems and their application to military programs. The position is responsible for understanding and establishing enterprise, operational, organizational, and performance metrics for the above areas. The Sr. Engineering Consultant must have the ability to analyze and provide recommendations on testing and metrics dealing with system and operational architectures; or coordinate with user community representatives throughout all phases of testing and development including requirements definition, clarification, prioritization, and alternatives; and applies emerging doctrine and tactics to testing system design while assessing the impact of programmatic and technical options on stated user requirements and doctrine. Performs analysis of documented user requirements and directs or assists in the design of test plans in support of user requirements. Collaborates directly with the users to establish the metric business rules that will provide the foundation of the organization's enterprise strategic plan. May participate in all phases of risk management assessment and software/hardware development. Responsible for ensuring that the designs and documentation support all applicable client, agency or industry standards, timelines, and budgets. Responsible for/or assists in the analysis of test results, documents conclusions, and makes recommendations as supported by such analysis. Provides Sr. Engineer Consulting support to theater/operational-level biometric staff elements, Combatant Commanders, Joint Task Force Commanders, and special purpose task forces. Must possess excellent math and statistics skills.

raw_data.title: F.I.T. 102: 4-Hour Overview of Facial Examination
raw_data.description: Four (4) hour class that covers a high-level overview of the basic tenets of the Facial Identification discipline for anyone interested in the discipline or using a Facial Recognition system. You will have the opportunity to “test” your skills with a couple of comparisons as well as interact with a skilled instructor to answer questions during the class. The start time for group classes can be tailored to the client's request.

raw_data.title: F.I.T. 103: 16-Hour Introductory Facial Examination Course
raw_data.description: A Facial Identification course created to meet  the minimum standard for training requirement for use of a Facial Recognition system. Topics include history, science & anatomy, morphological features of the face, and comparison methodologies relevant to the Facial Identification discipline. The class begins with lecture and later includes comparisons that are completed by the participants and reviewed by the instructor during the course. The class is typically taught four (4) hours each day over four (4) consecutive days. The start time can be tailored to the client's request.

raw_data.title: F.I.T. 301: 16-Hour Refresher Facial Examination Course
raw_data.description: A Facial Identification refresher course that builds on skills obtained from one of our 200 level courses. Participants can expect to further develop their skillset with this general review that offers pertinent information and updates relevant to the Facial Identification practice with a focus on adult-to-adult comparisons. The class is typically taught four (4) hours each day over four (4) consecutive days. The start time can be tailored to the client's request.

raw_data.title: F.I.T. 302: 16-Hour Refresher - Juvenile Images
raw_data.description: A Facial Identification refresher course that builds on skills obtained from one of our 200 level courses. Participants can expect to further develop their skillset with this general review that offers pertinent information and updates relevant to the Facial Identification practice with a focus on juvenile to juvenile and juvenile to adult comparisons. The class is typically taught four (4) hours each day over four (4) consecutive days. The start time can be tailored to the client's request.

raw_data.title: F.I.T. 303: 16-Hour Refresher - Population Variations
raw_data.description: A Facial Identification refresher course that builds on skills obtained from one of our 200 level courses. Participants can expect to further develop their skillset with this general review that offers pertinent information and updates relevant to the Facial Identification practice with a focus on adult-to-adult comparisons while focusing on the differences that are present amongst different populations. The class is typically taught four (4) hours each day over four (4) consecutive days. The start time can be tailored to the client's request.
